## Conversation
User asked (verbatim): "Write a GH action to automatically tag PRs that are in
draft for more than a month as stale, and close them automatically."

Then: "Do you have to inline the script or can you just write the script in
python alongside the workflow?" -> pivoted the implementation from an inline
actions/github-script (JavaScript-in-YAML) approach to a standalone Python
script invoked via `uv run`, matching the repo's existing pattern
(scripts/slack_digest.py + .github/workflows/slack-digest.yml, tldr.yaml).

Then: "Put this up as draft" -> commit + push + draft PR.

## Actions
- Explored .github/workflows/. Found close-inactive-prs.yml already uses
  actions/stale@v9 (keys off INACTIVITY via days-before-pr-stale). Key insight:
  actions/stale CANNOT filter on draft state, so it cannot express "in draft for
  N days". That justified a custom implementation.
- First wrote an inline actions/github-script@v7 version, validated with
  actionlint + node --check + a stubbed JS harness (8/8 logic checks).
- After the user's Python question, rewrote as scripts/close_stale_draft_prs.py:
  - PEP 723 inline deps (# /// script ... PyGithub>=2.0 ... ///), installed by
    `uv run` -- NO pyproject.toml change (same trick slack_digest.py uses).
  - Separated PURE logic (reduce_events, decide) from GitHub I/O so the core is
    unit-testable with plain data and zero mocking (per repo testing conventions).
  - scripts/test_close_stale_draft_prs.py: 13 tests, all passing.
  - Rewrote the workflow to checkout + setup-uv + `uv run scripts/...`, added a
    workflow_dispatch `dry_run` boolean input.
- Verified PyGithub API surface empirically via `uv run --with PyGithub python -c`
  introspection AND live `gh api` calls before writing code (see Discoveries).
- Validation: ruff format --check + ruff check (clean), actionlint (clean),
  13 unit tests pass, and a LIVE read-only --dry-run against wandb/weave.

