## Dead Ends
- Inline actions/github-script JS version: fully written, validated, then
  REPLACED by the Python version at the user's request. The git history has only
  the Python version (the JS was never committed).
- Considered actions/stale -> rejected (no draft filter).
- Considered the issues TIMELINE API for draft-age. Live `gh api` showed the
  timeline for PR #7103 did NOT include ready_for_review, while the issue-EVENTS
  API (/issues/{n}/events) DID. So we use pr.get_issue_events() (typed IssueEvent
  with .event/.created_at/.label), not the timeline.

## Hints for Future Agents
- DRAFT-AGE is computed from the latest `convert_to_draft` event, falling back to
  created_at. Do NOT simplify to created_at alone: a PR opened normally and later
  converted to draft has a misleading created_at and would be actioned too early.
- The label is `stale-draft`, deliberately NOT `stale`/`Stale`. GitHub label names
  are case-insensitive, so `stale` would collide with the `Stale` label that
  close-inactive-prs.yml's actions/stale manages. Keep them distinct.
- TWO-PHASE by design: mark at 30d-in-draft, then CLOSE only after the stale-draft
  label has aged `close_after_days` (7). Close timing keys off when WE labeled it
  (a `labeled` event in get_issue_events), NOT off draft-age -- this guarantees a
  warning window even for PRs that are already ancient on first run.
- The cheap pre-filter in _process_pr (skip young unlabeled drafts via created_at)
  is ONLY an optimization to avoid the per-PR events API call; `decide` re-validates
  everything and is the source of truth.
- Logging MUST use %-style args, not f-strings (ruff `G` / G004 is selected).
- scripts/ is NOT covered by pyright (include=[\"weave\"]) or strict mypy
  (disallow_untyped_defs only for module=\"weave.*\"). ANN rules are NOT selected.
  D (pydocstyle, google) IS selected but D10x (missing docstrings) is ignored.
- Run the tests isolated: `uv run --no-project --with pytest pytest
  scripts/test_close_stale_draft_prs.py -o addopts=\"\"` (clears the repo's
  addopts=-v; --no-project avoids syncing all of weave).
- Permissions: contents:read, pull-requests:write, issues:write. issues:write is
  ONLY for creating the stale-draft label (repo label management is under the
  issues scope); commenting/labeling/closing PRs is covered by pull-requests:write.

## Codebase Discoveries
- Live dry-run against wandb/weave: 346 OPEN PRs, of which 112 are drafts >30d old
  (some ~1000+ days). Enabling this as-is would mark 112 PRs on the first run and
  close them ~7d later -> real risk of GitHub SECONDARY rate limits on bulk writes
  (label+comment x112). Flagged to the user; offered a --max-actions-per-run cap
  (not yet built) and the dry_run input as mitigations.
- IssueEvent (PyGithub) exposes typed .event/.created_at/.label(.name); the
  /issues/{n}/events payload for a `labeled` event is
  {created_at, event:\"labeled\", label:{name}}. `ready_for_review` is present in
  /events (so `convert_to_draft` is too).
- pr.draft, pr.labels, pr.created_at come from the get_pulls list payload (no extra
  call). pr.get_issue_events() is a separate paginated call (only made for
  candidates that survive the pre-filter).
- Repo convention for script-backed workflows: PEP 723 inline deps + `uv run
  scripts/x.py` + GITHUB_TOKEN env (slack_digest.py / slack-digest.yml is the
  template).

